  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12444">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Name two breeds of livestock in each of the following classifications:
      horses, dairy cattle, beef cattle, sheep, hogs, poultry, and goats. Tell
      their principal uses and merits. Tell where the breeds originated.
      <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/qO_3pnlWtmE" target="_blank"
        >Different Types of Cattle Breeds Every Farmer Should Know (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/FiBBNX8WszQ" target="_blank"
        >Ten Popular Horse Breeds (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/X2dOtjQ7Afo" target="_blank"
        >Top 5 Best Sheep Breeds for Meat, Wool and Milk Production (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/oVLwITCidx0" target="_blank"
        >The 15 Best Pig Breeds for Your Farm (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/jctKRaHoiuQ" target="_blank"
        >5 Types of Chickens You Should Know About (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/3T2v89EsH_4" target="_blank"
        >Top 10 Best Goat Breeds for Milk &amp; Meat Production (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12445">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      List two diseases that afflict the animals in each of the classifications
      in requirement 1. Describe the symptoms of each disease and explain how
      each is contracted and how it could be prevented. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/HV-D5o7fhcQ" target="_blank"
        >Common Cattle Diseases: Treatment and Prevention (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/_ZeUDXMmSXE" target="_blank"
        >Health Problems in Horses (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/EwVUKrlCIm0" target="_blank"
        >20 Diseases of Goats and Sheep You Need to Know (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/CU9h9PFEFJQ" target="_blank"
        >Hidden Truth About Common Diseases of Pigs (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/IaBcFGTvo1g" target="_blank"
        >Unveiling the Dark Secrets of Common Poultry Diseases (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12446">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Draw models of the digestive tracts of ruminants, horses, pigs, and
      poultry. Explain how the differences in structure and function among these
      types of digestive tracts affect the nutritional management of these
      species.<br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/CJomFwt3eMs" target="_blank"
        >Digestion in Grass Eating Animals (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/8lqk7igz9L4" target="_blank"
        >The Horse's Digestive System (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/5OsmJ_ERO3g" target="_blank"
        >Types of Livestock Digestive Systems (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12447">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Select one type of animal: beef cow, dairy cow, horse, sheep, goat, or
      hog, or a poultry flock, and tell how you would properly manage it.
      Include in your discussion nutritional (feeding) concerns, housing,
      disease prevention, waste control/removal, breeding programs, and
      biosecurity as appropriate. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
      <a href="https://youtu.be/JNCPdG8jSKI?si=nt_jtn9irpLbZJSd" target="_blank"
        >Raising Dexter Cattle for Beef: Everything You Ever Wanted to Know
        (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/58wsqGWK1kk?si=Jx3145QIFAa_fz1-" target="_blank"
        >How To Raise a Dairy Cow: Step-by-Step Guide for Beginners! (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/_KpkB7X3wIM" target="_blank"
        >How To Raise Sheep for Beginners on 2.5 Acres or Less (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/7rNbUVZjBc8" target="_blank"
        >Raising Goats 101 (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/h0D1N9oDEUE" target="_blank"
        >An Introduction to Raising Pigs on Pasture (video)</a
      ><br />
      <a href="https://youtu.be/aQMLQo-u7Sc" target="_blank"
        >10 Things To Know Before You Buy Backyard Chickens (video)</a
      >
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12448">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12448 mb-requirement-id-12450">
        (a) Explain how agricultural producers make desired improvements to
        their stock through breeding practices and programs. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/TZaHQV22zqM" target="_blank"
          >How to Breed a Better Chicken (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12448 mb-requirement-id-12451">
        (b) Explain the terms pure breeding and cross breeding. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/wjF1gxO0LmU" target="_blank"
          >How Crossbreeding Works—How to Move From Hybrid Goats to Pure
          Pedigree Lines in Goat Farming (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12448 mb-requirement-id-12452">
        (c) List two modern technologies used in the production of horses, dairy
        cattle, beef cattle, sheep, hogs, poultry, or goats, and tell what the
        advantages are of using the technology. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/3kIAGwHSsns" target="_blank"
          >Using Nuclear Science to Improve Animal Breeding (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/wJynHHapJx8" target="_blank"
          >Improving Health &amp; Fertility for Each Cow With MooMonitor+
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/KEDqZc1uYNQ" target="_blank"
          >From Satellites to Sound: Practical AI Tools for Dairy and Poultry
          Farming (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12401">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      Complete ONE of the following options:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12401 mb-requirement-id-12402">
        <strong>Option A—Beef Cattle.</strong> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12402 mb-requirement-id-12403">
        (1) Visit a farm or ranch where beef cattle are produced under any of
        these systems: feeding market cattle for harvest, cow/calf operation
        (producing cattle for sale to commercial feeders), or producing purebred
        cattle for sale as breeding stock to others.<br />
        Talk with the operator to learn how the cattle were handled, fed,
        weighed, and shipped. Describe what you saw and explain what you
        learned. If you cannot visit a cattle ranch or farm, view a video from a
        breed association, or research the internet (with your parent or
        guardian's permission) for information on beef cattle production. Tell
        about your findings. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/1kA7wQCIoqI" target="_blank"
          >A Tour of Our Cattle Ranch - 20,000+ Head of Cattle per Year
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12402 mb-requirement-id-12404">
        (2) Sketch a plan of a feedlot to include its forage and grain storage
        facilities, and loading chute for 30 or more fattening steers; or sketch
        a corral plan with cutting and loading chutes for handling 50 or more
        beef cows and their calves at one time. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://bookstore.ksre.ksu.edu/pubs/planning-and-designing-cattle-feedlots_MF2316.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Planning and Designing Cattle Feedlots (PDF)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://agrilifeextension.tamu.edu/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/Corral_Working_Facilities_for_Beef_Cattle_OSU_6.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Corral and Working Facilities for Beef Cattle (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12402 mb-requirement-id-12405">
        (3) Make a sketch showing the principal wholesale and retail cuts of
        beef. Tell about the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) dual grading
        system of beef. Tell the basis of each grade in each system. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/ks83UksLbmg" target="_blank"
          >Basic Meat Cuts &amp; Grades (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.webstaurantstore.com/guide/965/types-of-beef-cuts.html"
          target="_blank"
          >Types of Beef Cuts (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.canr.msu.edu/montcalm-county/uploads/files/Market%20Beef%20Wholesale%20Cuts.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Beef Wholesale and Retail Cuts (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12402 mb-requirement-id-12406">
        (4) Define the following terms: bull, steer, bullock, cow, heifer,
        freemartin, heiferette, and calf. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/GA-QnF7J4Wg" target="_blank"
          >What's the Difference Between a Steer vs. Bull? Cow vs. Heifer?
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://thevetdesk.com/pet-lifestyle/cattle/how-tell-cattle-cow-bull-heifer-steer/"
          target="_blank"
          >How to Tell If Cattle Are Cows, Bulls, Heifers, or Steers
          (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12401 mb-requirement-id-12407">
        <strong>Option B—Dairy.</strong> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12407 mb-requirement-id-12408">
        (1) Tell how a cow or a goat converts forage and grain into milk.
        Explain the differences in feeds typically used for dairy cows versus
        those fed to beef cows. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/Vbwwl3lLOqw" target="_blank"
          >How Cows Create Milk—3D Animated Tour (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/4PFmkRak8hw" target="_blank"
          >What Cows Eat To Produce Milk (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/fsZl7-oLxWI" target="_blank"
          >How To Feed a Beef Cow (Corn vs Hay) (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12407 mb-requirement-id-12409">
        (2) Make a chart showing the components in cow's milk or goat's milk.
        Chart the amount of each component. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Animal%20Science/milk_components_graph_guidelines_worksheet.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Milk Components Chart (PDF)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.healthline.com/nutrition/milk#nutrition"
          target="_blank"
          >Milk 101: Nutrition Facts and Health Effects (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.healthline.com/health/benefits-of-goat-milk#Goat-s-milk-vs-cow-s-milk"
          target="_blank"
          >Goat's Milk: Is This the Right Milk for You? (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12407 mb-requirement-id-12410">
        (3) Explain the requirements for producing grade A milk. Tell how and
        why milk is pasteurized. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/yJ3TqOXRqk4" target="_blank"
          >What Is Pasteurization? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12407 mb-requirement-id-12411">
        (4) Tell about the kinds of equipment used for milking and the
        sanitation standards that must be met on dairy farms. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/JfLTcy15Tik" target="_blank"
          >How Are Cows Actually Milked? Explained by a Dairy Veterinarian
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12407 mb-requirement-id-12412">
        (5) Define the following terms: bull, cow, steer, heifer, springer,
        buck, doe, and kid. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://merrymeadowsok.com/goat-terminology-101/"
          target="_blank"
          >Goat Terminology (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12407 mb-requirement-id-12413">
        (6) Visit a dairy farm or a milk processing plant. Describe what you saw
        and explain what you learned. If you cannot visit a dairy farm or
        processing plant, view a video from a breed or dairy association, or
        research the internet (with your parent or guardian's permission) for
        information on dairying. Tell about your findings. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/1hrLeSQSdw4" target="_blank"
          >Guided Barn Tour! Modern Dairy Farm Tour (Part 1) (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/U32W389XDbo" target="_blank"
          >Robotic Dairy Barn Tour (Part 2)—The One You've Been Asking For
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/uhXNHVlQnBc" target="_blank"
          >How They Process Milk In Factory With Modern Food Processing
          Technology | How It's Made (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12401 mb-requirement-id-12414">
        <strong>Option C—Horse.</strong> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12414 mb-requirement-id-12415">
        (1) Make a sketch of a useful saddle horse barn and exercise yard.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12414 mb-requirement-id-12416">
        (2) Tell about the history of the horse and the benefits it has brought
        to people. Using the four breeds of horses you chose in requirement 1,
        discuss the different special uses of each breed. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/px9Ljv0bits" target="_blank"
          >How Horses Went From Food to Friends (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/kZoTvXvV02A" target="_blank"
          >How Horses Took Over North America (Twice) (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/FRuSrJXs5-Q" target="_blank"
          >Where Did Domesticated Horses Come From? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12414 mb-requirement-id-12417">
        (3) Define the following terms: mare, stallion, gelding, foal, colt,
        filly; mustang, quarter horse, draft horse, pacer, trotter; pinto,
        calico, palomino, roan, overo, and tobiano. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/jWkWetXkgO8" target="_blank"
          >What's the Difference Between a Mare, Stallion, Gelding, Colt, and a
          Pony? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.tiktok.com/@spendthriftfarm/video/7042307754253356335"
          target="_blank"
          >Understanding Common Horse Terms (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.willowbrookridingcentre.co.uk/mustang-horse-facts/"
          target="_blank"
          >10 Facts About Mustang Horses That Make Them So Special (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://horsenameideas.com/draft-horse-vs-quarter-horse/"
          target="_blank"
          >Draft Horse vs Quarter Horse: Comprehensive Comparison Guide
          (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://insiderhorse.com/horse-coat-patterns/" target="_blank"
          >The Different Coat Patterns Found in Horses &amp; How to Identify
          Them (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12414 mb-requirement-id-12418">
        (4) Visit a horse farm. Describe what you saw and explain what you
        learned. If you cannot visit a horse farm, view a video from a breed
        association, or research the internet (with your parent or guardian's
        permission) for information on horses. Tell about your findings.
        <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/NbXQn8-VMww" target="_blank"
          >Inside Claiborne Farm—Home of Secretariat &amp; Racing Legends
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12414 mb-requirement-id-12419">
        (5) Outline the proper feeding of a horse doing light work. Explain why
        the amount and kind of feed will change according to the kind of horse
        and the work it does. Describe what colic is, what can cause it, and its
        symptoms. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/DqN3Ps01Qp8" target="_blank"
          >The 7 Golden Rules of Feeding Horses (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/uB-o9e6_rxM" target="_blank"
          >Colic in Horses: Horse Vet Explains What Owners Should Know
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12401 mb-requirement-id-12420">
        <b>Option D—Sheep or Goat.</b> Choose one and do ALL of the following
        based upon the choice:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12420 mb-requirement-id-12424">
        (1) Make a sketch of a live lamb or goat. Show the location of the
        various wholesale and retail cuts. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/vP_OH7FI-4Y" target="_blank"
          >Lamb &amp; Goat Cuts (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.webstaurantstore.com/guide/1273/types-of-lamb-cuts.html"
          target="_blank"
          >Types of Lamb Cuts (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12420 mb-requirement-id-12425">
        (2) Discuss how wools are sorted and graded. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/twn79JnSZj8" target="_blank"
          >Mid States Wool: Grading Process (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/0Owp99Xi8is" target="_blank"
          >British Wool—Wool Grading and Selling at Auction (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12420 mb-requirement-id-12625">
        (3) List products that can be made from the milk. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://agritopic.com/dairy-industry/dairy-products-list-a-comprehensive-guide/"
          target="_blank"
          >Dairy Products List: 50+ Dairy Foods (What Counts As Dairy?)
          (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12420 mb-requirement-id-12421">
        (4) Based on your choice, do ONE of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12421 mb-requirement-id-12422">
        (a) Raise a lamb or goat from weaning to market weight. Keep records of
        feed intake, weight gains, medication, vaccination, and mortality.
        Present your records to your counselor for review. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://ia601306.us.archive.org/26/items/GuideToSheepAndGoatProduction/Guide-to-Sheep-and-Goat-Production.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Illustrated Guide to Sheep and Goat Production (PDF)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Animal%20Science/lamb_goat_market_record_fillable_polished_v2.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Lamb or Goat Record Book (PDF)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://threelittlegoats.com/free-goat-health-printable/"
          target="_blank"
          >Goat Record Book (PDF)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://mamaonthehomestead.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/The-Sheep-Record-Book.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Sheep Record Book (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12421 mb-requirement-id-12423">
        (b) Visit a farm or ranch where sheep or goats are raised. Describe what
        you saw and explain what you learned. If you cannot visit a sheep or
        goat farm or ranch, view a video from a breed association, or research
        the internet (with your parent or guardian's permission) for information
        on sheep or goats. Tell about your findings. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/iYpfK-GXJ9c" target="_blank"
          >Redwood Hill Goat Farm: The Land of Happy Goats! (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/gfuc7mRPEpw" target="_blank"
          >Flax Family Farms—Utica Kansas (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://youtu.be/AATXu2Hl07I" target="_blank"
          >1000 Sheep: Expert Farmer Interview and Farm Tour of Slatted Shed,
          Handling System and Sheep (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12420 mb-requirement-id-12427">
        (5) Define the following terms for a sheep (wether, ewe, ram, and lamb)
        OR a goat (doe, nanny, kid, buck, and billy). <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://www.sheep101.info/sheepandlambs.html" target="_blank"
          >Sheep Terminology (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://merrymeadowsok.com/goat-terminology-101/"
          target="_blank"
          >Goat Terminology (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12401 mb-requirement-id-12428">
        <strong>Option E—Hog.</strong> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12428 mb-requirement-id-12432">
        (1) Make a sketch showing the principal wholesale and retail cuts of
        pork. Tell about the recommended USDA grades of pork. Tell the basis for
        each grade. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://www.farmcreditofvirginias.com/sites/default/files/Knowledge%20Center%20Assets/Youth%20Showbox/Retail%20Cuts%20of%20Pork-Infographic.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Retail Cuts of Pork (PDF)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.webstaurantstore.com/guide/1114/types-of-pork-cuts.html"
          target="_blank"
          >Types of Pork Cuts (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12428 mb-requirement-id-12433">
        (2) Outline in writing the proper feeding programs used from the
        breeding of a gilt or sow through the weaning of the litter. Discuss the
        feeding programs for the growth and finishing periods. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://www.asi.k-state.edu/extension/swine/swinenutritionguide/"
          target="_blank"
          >Swine Nutrition Guide (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://americankunekunepigsociety.org/feeding-kunekunes/"
          target="_blank"
          >Feeding Kunekunes (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12428 mb-requirement-id-12429">
        (3) Do ONE of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12429 mb-requirement-id-12430">
        (a) Raise a feeder pig from weaning to market weight. Keep records of
        feed intake, weight gains, medication, vaccination, and mortality.
        Present your records to your counselor for review. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Animal%20Science/pig_market_record_fillable_polished_v2.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Pig Project Record Book (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12429 mb-requirement-id-12431">
        (b) Visit a farm where hogs are produced, or visit a packing plant
        handling hogs. Describe what you saw and explain what you learned. If
        you cannot visit a hog production unit or packing plant, view a video
        from a packer or processor, or research the internet (with your parent
        or guardian's permission) for information on hogs. Tell about your
        findings. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/jSXeWwyymbA" target="_blank"
          >The Industrial Meat Machine: How Thousands of Pigs Are Processed
          Daily (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12428 mb-requirement-id-12434">
        (4) Define the following terms: gilt, sow, barrow, and boar. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://www.porkcdn.com/sites/porkorg/library/2016/10/Pigtionary.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Pigtionary (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12401 mb-requirement-id-12435">
        <strong>Option F—Avian.</strong> Do ALL of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12435 mb-requirement-id-12440">
        (1) Make a sketch of a layer house or broiler house showing nests,
        roosts, feeders, waterers, and means of ventilation. Explain how
        insulation, ventilation, temperature controls, automatic lights, and
        other environmental controls are used to protect birds from heat, cold,
        and bad weather. Explain the importance of light for egg production.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://agriculture.institute/poultry-housing-and-management/designing-layer-houses-buildings-dimensions-cage-arrangements/"
          target="_blank"
          >Designing Layer Houses: Buildings, Dimensions, and Cage Arrangements
          (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://agriculture.institute/poultry-housing-and-management/constructing-broiler-house-area-dimensions-tips/"
          target="_blank"
          >Guidelines for Constructing a Broiler House: Area, Dimensions, and
          Construction Tips (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12435 mb-requirement-id-12441">
        (2) Explain why overcrowding is dangerous for poultry flocks. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a href="https://youtu.be/uwUg5eIclHQ" target="_blank"
          >The #1 Mistake Chicken Keepers Make (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12435 mb-requirement-id-12442">
        (3) Tell about the grading of eggs. Describe the classes of chicken
        meat. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/toMJUI33kAo" target="_blank"
          >The Difference Between Grade AA, A, and B Eggs (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.ams.usda.gov/sites/default/files/media/PoultryPictureSeriesPrintVersion.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >A Guide to U.S. Graded Chicken (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12435 mb-requirement-id-12436">
        (4) Do ONE of the following:
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12436 mb-requirement-id-12437">
        (a) Manage an egg-producing flock for five months. Keep records of feed
        purchased, eggs sold, medication, vaccination, and mortality. Present
        your records to your counselor for review. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Animal%20Science/egg_record_book_fillable_polished_v2.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Egg Producing Record Book (Fillable) (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12436 mb-requirement-id-12438">
        (b) Raise five chickens from hatching. Keep records of feed intake,
        weight gains, medication, vaccination, and mortality. Present your
        records to your counselor for review. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Animal%20Science/chicken_growth_record_fillable_polished_v2.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Chicken Growth Record Book (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12436 mb-requirement-id-12439">
        (c) Visit a commercial avian production facility. Describe what you saw
        and explain what you learned. If you cannot visit a commercial facility,
        view a video from a poultry association, or research the internet (with
        your parent or guardian's permission) for information on poultry
        production. Tell about your findings. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a href="https://youtu.be/-ZBXNpLQ1Y0" target="_blank"
          >Inside the Chicken Factory: Processing Millions of Chickens for Meat
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12435 mb-requirement-id-12443">
        (5) Define the following terms: chick, pullet, hen, cockerel, cock, and
        capon. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://mannapro.com/blogs/news/chicken-terminology-101"
          target="_blank"
          >Chick-Tionary (website / video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
